  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/943083470" />
    <a title="Blues" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3345245-blues"><img alt="Blues" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/m_50x66-82093808bca726cb3249a493fbd3bd0f.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/943083470?book_show_action=true">May 20, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Blues" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Blues" href="/user/show/3345245-blues">Blues</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="ebook 9780385352086" href="/book/show/18779992-the-painter">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer943083470" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer405647559598086696">Like many, I truly enjoyed and was moved by &quot;The Dog Stars&quot;. This novel, however, couldn&apos;t be more different in that regard.<br/><br/>It was somewhat of a Sisyphusian effort to work through and finish as the protagonist was unlikable (and unbelievable), the plot overly contrived (and unbelievable) and the overall story line and action cookie cutter and formulaic. (Big, tough, talented, independent, uncompromising, moody artist...babe magnet...finds himself lamenting and struggling to survive the hellish l</span>
  <span id="freeText405647559598086696" style="display:none">Like many, I truly enjoyed and was moved by "The Dog Stars". This novel, however, couldn't be more different in that regard.<br /><br />It was somewhat of a Sisyphusian effort to work through and finish as the protagonist was unlikable (and unbelievable), the plot overly contrived (and unbelievable) and the overall story line and action cookie cutter and formulaic. (Big, tough, talented, independent, uncompromising, moody artist...babe magnet...finds himself lamenting and struggling to survive the hellish life he has entirely and unnecessarily brought upon himself. Sigh...)<br /><br />If it wasn't for the fact that I was personally familiar with many of the locales, including Paonia, from my travels, I don't know that I could have made it all the way through.<br /><br />Having read "The Dog Stars" I have no doubt that Mr. Heller is capable of producing more excellent work and I eagerly await the publication.<br />Sadly, this book was a step in entirely the wrong direction, in my humble opinion.</span>
  <a data-text-id="405647559598086696" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


